# Rust Types & Traits

The type system is the design tool. Make illegal states unrepresentable.

## Newtype pattern

- Wrap primitives in newtypes to prevent mix-ups: `struct UserId(u64)` not `type UserId = u64`
- Implement `Display`, `Debug`, `From`/`Into`, and `Deref` on newtypes as appropriate
- Use `#[repr(transparent)]` when the newtype must have the same memory layout as the inner type

## Enums over booleans

- Replace `bool` parameters that encode state with an enum:
  ```rust
  // BAD
  fn connect(host: &str, tls: bool) { ... }
  // GOOD
  enum Tls { Enabled, Disabled }
  fn connect(host: &str, tls: Tls) { ... }
  ```
- Use `enum` to model all variants of a domain concept — the compiler will enforce exhaustiveness

## Structs

- Prefer named fields over tuple structs for anything with more than one field
- Use `#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq)]` as the default; add `Eq`, `Hash`, `Ord` when semantically correct
- Use `Default` derive or implement it when a zero/empty value is meaningful
- Use the builder pattern (or `..Default::default()`) for structs with many optional fields

## Generics

- Use generics for compile-time polymorphism; use `dyn Trait` (trait objects) only when you genuinely need runtime dispatch or heterogeneous collections
- Bound at the call site, not the struct definition, unless the bound is a core invariant of the type
- Prefer `impl Trait` in argument position over `&dyn Trait` to keep dispatch static:
  ```rust
  // Prefer this
  fn process(item: impl Read) { ... }
  // Over this (unless heterogeneous)
  fn process(item: &dyn Read) { ... }
  ```
- Use `where` clauses when bounds become too long to fit on the signature line

## Trait design

- Design small, focused traits — one responsibility per trait (like `Iterator`, `Display`, `From`)
- Implement standard library traits (`Display`, `From`, `Into`, `Iterator`, `Index`) before inventing custom ones
- Do not add blanket implementations carelessly — they affect all downstream crates
- Use associated types (`type Item`) instead of type parameters on traits when there is only one natural choice per implementation

## Phantom types & type state

- Use `PhantomData<T>` to carry type information without runtime cost
- Use type-state patterns to encode protocol correctness at compile time:
  ```rust
  struct Connection<State> { inner: TcpStream, _state: PhantomData<State> }
  struct Connected;
  struct Disconnected;
  impl Connection<Disconnected> {
      fn connect(self) -> Connection<Connected> { ... }
  }
  ```
